📌 When do you make migrations?
✅ YES — whenever your models change

You create a migration when you:

Schema changes:
add/remove columns
rename fields
change types (str → int, etc.)
add constraints (unique, nullable, etc.)
add/remove tables
❌ NOT needed for:
changing Python-only logic
FastAPI routes
business logic
validations not stored in DB
🔁 Typical workflow (VERY IMPORTANT)
1. Change your model
email: str
phone: str | None = None
2. Create migration
alembic revision --autogenerate -m "add phone to user"
3. Review migration (IMPORTANT step)

Open:

alembic/versions/xxx_add_phone_to_user.py

Make sure it makes sense.

4. Apply migration
alembic upgrade head
⚠️ Golden rule (don’t skip this)

Never blindly run:

alembic upgrade head

without checking the generated migration.

🧠 Why Alembic showed “removed table users”

This is important:

It usually means one of these:

1. Model not imported properly in env.py

or

2. SQLModel metadata not fully loaded when Alembic runs
✅ Best practice fix (do this now)

In alembic/env.py, ensure:

from app import models  # IMPORTANT: triggers model registration

NOT just:

from app.models import User

You want ALL models loaded.

🚀 Production workflow summary

You will always do this cycle:

1. edit models.py
2. alembic revision --autogenerate
3. check migration file
4. alembic upgrade head
💡 Extra tips (important)
✔ Use meaningful migration names

Bad:

"update"

Good:

"add user profile fields"
"create orders table"
✔ Never edit DB manually in production

Always go through Alembic.

✔ If something breaks

You can reset locally:

alembic downgrade base
alembic upgrade head
